Absorbance values were recorded for 82 full term pregnant females. A gestation length of 62 days was assumed (Gier, 1968, Kennelly, 1978) and the OD readings were aligned using the day of parturition as the reference point. Partitioning of the gestation period into weekly intervals showed optical density increasing by week 4 (Table 3
). When more than one sample was collected, it was possible to estimate the day of gestation based upon when a coyote first showed a positive relaxin test result (Table 4
). Under these conditions, the earliest positive result was obtained at an estimated 23 days gestation; on days 24–27 results either were negative, indeterminate, or positive. However, from day 28 on, all results were positive and had an OD ≥ 0.100 (Fig. 1
). We also note that while some negative and indeterminate results were recorded, at least 90% of the samples collected on days 25–27 were interpreted as positive (Table 4).
